  "prompt_text": "Write an algorithm to detect a cycle in a linked list. What is its space and time complexity?",
  "response_text": "**Detecting a Cycle in a Linked List Algorithm**\n\nThe algorithm to detect a cycle in a linked list can be implemented using Floyd's Tortoise and Hare (Cycle Detection) algorithm, also known as the \"tortoise and the hare\" algorithm. This algorithm uses two pointers that move at different speeds through the linked list. If there is a cycle, these two pointers will eventually meet.\n\n### Code Implementation\n\n```python\nclass Node:\n    def __init__(self, data):\n        self.data = data\n        self.next = None\n\ndef detect_cycle(head):\n    \"\"\"\n    Detects a cycle in a linked list using Floyd's Tortoise and Hare algorithm.\n\n    Args:\n        head (Node): The head of the linked list.\n\n    Returns:\n        bool: True if a cycle is detected, False otherwise.\n    \"\"\"\n    tortoise = head\n    hare = head\n\n    while tortoise and hare and hare.next:\n        tortoise = tortoise.next  # Move the tortoise one step at a time\n        hare = hare.next.next  # Move the hare two steps at a time\n\n        if tortoise == hare:  # If the tortoise and hare meet, there is a cycle\n            return True\n\n    return False  # If the tortoise or hare reaches the end of the list, there is no cycle\n\n# Example usage:\n# Create a linked list with a cycle\nnode1 = Node(1)\nnode2 = Node(2)\nnode3 = Node(3)\nnode4 = Node(4)\n\nnode1.next = node2\nnode2.next = node3\nnode3.next = node4\nnode4.next = node2  # Create a cycle\n\nprint(detect_cycle(node1))  # Output: True\n\n# Create a linked list without a cycle\nnode5 = Node(5)\nnode6 = Node(6)\nnode7 = Node(7)\n\nnode5.next = node6\nnode6.next = node7\n\nprint(detect_cycle(node5))  # Output: False\n```\n\n### Time and Space Complexity\n\n*   Time complexity: O(n), where n is the number of nodes in the linked list. This is because in the worst-case scenario, the tortoise and hare pointers will traverse the entire linked list.\n*   Space complexity: O(1), as the algorithm only uses a constant amount of space to store the tortoise and hare pointers.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 9\nP (Pattern Recognition): 8\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 8\nQ (Query Interpretation): 9\nC (Contextual Awareness): 8\nY (Affective Modeling): 6\nF (Flexibility): 8\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END RATINGS---",
